@AwesomeC Because it's emulated.
An emulator uses the original files of the game/software and recreates the platform, running in a sort of container, so that the game/software can be successfully run even on other hardware (for example, a Gamecube emulator for the XBOX360 would let you play Gamecube games on the XBOX360 (just an example)).
Here (with Dolphin (the emulator)), an effort to emulate the platform (Gamecube) on completely different hardware (the Gamecube is built on the PowerPC architecture and Dolphin is for x86 architecture), but since Nintendo did not and NEVER WILL release the technical documents that would make developing an emulator straightforward, the hardware (for the emulator) must be reverse-engineered, which pretty much equates to stabbing in the dark in a room the size of a city (they are doing really well so far).  So if you think that the emulator should be faster, donate money or time to the Dolphin project.
